mportant social issues such as political authority, community identity, and gender differences are represented in these narratives. Unlike other styles of Indian theater, the nautanki does not draw on the pan-Indian religious epics such as the Ramayana or the Mahabharata for its subjects. Indeed, their storylines tend to center on the vicissitudes of stranded heroines in the throes of melodramatic romance. Whereas nautanki performers were once much in demand, live performances now are rare and nautanki increasingly reaches its audiences through electronic media—records, cassettes, films, television. In spite of this change, the theater form still functions as an effective conduit in the cultural flow that connects urban centers and the hinterland in an ongoing process of exchange.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFolk drama, HindixHistory and criticism. 0aFolk drama, Hindi. 0aNautankizIndiaxHistory and criticism. 0aNautanki. 0aTheaterxInde. 0aTheaterxIndia. 0aTheaterzIndia. 0aTheater. 0aThéâtre populaire hindixHistoire et critique. 0aThéâtrexInde. 4adance. 4adancing. 4adrama. 4aperformance. 4atelevision. 4atheatre studies. 4atheatre. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aancient plays.  aasian studies.  aclassic plays.  acommunity identity.  acultural anthropology.  adance.  agender differences.  aindian theater.  alive performances.  amelodramatic romance.  amusic.  anautanki performance.  anorthern india.  apoetry.  apolitical authority.  apopular story lines.  aprofane stories.  asocial issues.  astranded heroines.  athespian.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520910881?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degr